# DownloadService

Rust microservice that serves media files (photos & videos) over HTTP and exposes them as an HLS playlist (.m3u8).

## Overview

- Language  : Rust (Tokio + Axum)
- Port      : 3001
- Media dir : /media (mounted volume in Docker, ../media locally)

## Endpoints

### GET /health
Liveness probe. Returns plain text "ok".

### GET /playlist.m3u8
Returns an HLS v3 VOD playlist containing all media files found in MEDIA_DIR.
Photos are assigned PHOTO_DURATION seconds each; videos VIDEO_DURATION seconds each.

Supported photo extensions : jpg, jpeg, png, gif, webp, bmp
Supported video extensions : mp4, ts, m4s, mov, avi, mkv, webm

Query parameter:
  files=name1.mp4,name2.jpg   (optional) comma-separated list of file names to include.
                               If omitted, all media files in MEDIA_DIR are returned.

Example:
  GET /playlist.m3u8
  GET /playlist.m3u8?files=Sustainable%20Thai%20Cuisine%20at%20Baan%20Tepa.mp4

Response: Content-Type: application/vnd.apple.mpegurl (215 bytes for one entry — this is normal, it is a text manifest not the video itself)

### GET /files/:name
Serves the raw media file with full Range-request support (required for video seeking).

Example:
  GET /files/Sustainable%20Thai%20Cuisine%20at%20Baan%20Tepa.mp4

## How HLS playback works

1. Frontend requests GET /playlist.m3u8 → receives the small text manifest.
2. HLS player reads the manifest and requests each segment (GET /files/:name).
3. Video is streamed with Range requests, enabling seek/scrub.

The .m3u8 file is intentionally small (text only). This is the expected behaviour.

## Frontend integration

Native HLS is only supported in Safari. For all other browsers use hls.js:

  <video id="video" controls></video>
  <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/hls.js@latest"></script>
  <script>
    const src = "http://localhost:3001/playlist.m3u8";
    const video = document.getElementById("video");
    if (Hls.isSupported()) {
      const hls = new Hls();
      hls.loadSource(src);
      hls.attachMedia(video);
    } else if (video.canPlayType("application/vnd.apple.mpegurl")) {
      video.src = src;
    }
  </script>

If the frontend runs on a different origin, enable CORS (see Environment Variables below).

## Via nginx gateway

The nginx gateway strips the /api/download prefix and forwards to this service:

  GET http://localhost/api/download/playlist.m3u8
  GET http://localhost/api/download/playlist.m3u8?files=video.mp4
  GET http://localhost/api/download/files/video.mp4

## Environment Variables

  HTTP_ADDR       Bind address                         (default: 0.0.0.0:3001)
  MEDIA_DIR       Absolute path to media folder        (default: /media)
  FILES_BASE_URL  Segment URL prefix in the playlist   (default: files)
  PHOTO_DURATION  Seconds assigned to each photo       (default: 5)
  VIDEO_DURATION  Seconds assigned to each video       (default: 10)
  RUST_LOG        Log level (info/debug/warn/error)     (default: info)

## Running locally

  cd DownloadService
  cargo run

Reads ../.env or environment variables. Media files must be placed in ../media/.

## Running with Docker

  docker compose up download_service

The ./media folder at workspace root is mounted read-only at /media inside the container.
Drop media files in ./media/ and they are immediately available without rebuilding.

## Security

- Path traversal is rejected: file names containing / \ or .. return 400 Bad Request.
- Unknown file extensions are silently skipped.
- Missing files are silently skipped (no 404 leak for individual segments).
- Media volume is mounted read-only (:ro) in Docker.
